{{redirect|Cold store|the TV sitcom episode of that title|List_of_Are_You_Being_Served%3F_episodes#Series_3_(1975){{!}}Are You Being Served}} A '''cool store''' or '''cold store''' is a large [[refrigeration|refrigerated]] room or building designed for storage of goods in an environment below the outdoor temperature. Products needing refrigeration include [[fruit]], [[vegetable]]s, [[seafood]] and [[meat]]. Cold stores are often located near [[shipping port]]s used for import/export of produce.
Cool stores have been an essential part of the shipping industry since the late 19th century. [[Christian Salvesen]] expanded from a small Scottish whaling company when they established a cold store in [[Grimsby]], then a major fishing port.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/opinion/15963682.Obituary___Sir_Gerald_Elliot__former_chairman_of_Christian_Salvesen_and_patron_of_the_arts_in_Scotland/|title=Obituary - Sir Gerald Elliot, former chairman of Christian Salvesen and patron of the arts in Scotland|newspaper=Herald Scotland|date=8 February 2018|accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref> Nine Elms Cold Store, constructed in 1965, could hold 16,000 tons of meat, cheese and butter. It closed in 1979 and was used by squatters and various illegal activities before being demolished towards the end of the century.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.timeout.com/london/blog/16-creepy-london-stories-to-get-you-in-the-mood-for-halloween-103116|title=16 creepy London stories to get you in the mood for Halloween|first=Andy|last=Hill|work=Time Out|date=31 October 2016|accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref>
The stores themselves vary in size. A thirty hectare (74 acre) cold store with 200,000 tonne capacity was planned for [[Wuhan, China]]. <ref name="wuhan"> {{Cite web | last = Fruitnet | title = China’s biggest cool store planned for Wuhan {{!}} Fruitnet | work = The Global Fresh Produce Portal | accessdate = 2010-01-02 | date = 2008-10-31 | url = http://www.fruitnet.com/content.aspx?ttid=15&sid=96&cid=1812 }} </ref>
