[[File:Ecard-rückseite-österreich.png|thumb|Sample European Health Insurance Card from Austria (reverse).]]
[[File:Elektronische Gesundheitskarte Mustermann RS.svg|thumb|German card]]
[[File:Carte Européenne d'Assurance Maladie France.jpg|thumb|Sample French EHIC]]
[[File:EHIC Slovenia.jpg|thumb|Slovenian card]]

The '''European Health Insurance Card''' (or '''EHIC''') is issued free of charge and allows anyone who is insured by or covered by a statutory social security scheme of the [[European Economic Area|EEA]] countries and [[Switzerland]] to receive medical treatment in another member state free or at a reduced cost, if that treatment becomes necessary during their visit (for example, due to illness or an accident), or if they have a chronic [[pre-existing condition]] which requires care such as [[kidney dialysis]].  The term of validity of the card varies according to the issuing country.

The intention of the scheme is to allow people to continue their stay in a country without having to return home for medical care; as such, it does not cover people who have visited a country for the purpose of obtaining medical care, nor does it cover care, such as many types of dental treatment, which can be delayed until the individual returns to his or her home country. The costs not covered by self-liability fees are paid by the issuing country, which is usually the country of residence but may also be the country where one receives the most pension from.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/society/reality-check/2015/aug/11/are-foreigners-gaming-nhs-pay-medical-treatment-abroad-ehic</ref>

It only covers healthcare which is normally covered by a statutory health care system in the visited country, so it does not render [[travel insurance]] obsolete.

The card was phased in from 1 June 2004 and throughout 2005, becoming the sole healthcare entitlement document on 1 January 2006. The card is applicable in all [[France|French]] [[overseas department]]s ([[Martinique]], [[Guadeloupe]], [[Réunion]], and [[French Guiana]]) as they are part of the EEA, but not [[Special Member State territories and the European Union|non-EEA dependent territories]] such as [[Jersey]], the [[Isle of Man]], [[Aruba]], or [[French Polynesia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/travel-and-living-abroad/travel-advice-by-country/asia-oceania/french-polynesia |title=UK FCO Travel Advice: French Polynesia |publisher=Fco.gov.uk |date=2012-09-12 |accessdate=2012-10-12}}</ref> However, there are agreements for the use of the EHIC in the [[Faroe Islands]] and [[Greenland]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/travel-and-living-abroad/travel-advice-by-country/europe/denmark |title=UK FCO Travel Advice: Denmark |publisher=Fco.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-10-12}}</ref> even though they are not in the EEA.

The reason for the existence of this card, is that the right to health care in Europe is based on the country of legal residence, not the country of citizenship. Therefore, a passport is not enough to receive health care. It is however possible that a photo ID document is asked for, since the European Health Insurance Card does not contain a photo.

In some cases, even if a person is covered by the health insurance of an [[European Union member state|EU country]], one is not eligible for a European Health Insurance Card. For instance, in Romania, a person who is currently insured has to have been insured for the previous five years to be eligible.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libertatea.ro/stire/cardul-european-de-asigurari-de-sanatate-eliberat-gratuit-250099.html |title=Cardul european de asigurări de sănătate, eliberat gratuit |publisher=Libertatea.ro |date=2009-08-01 |accessdate=2012-10-12}}</ref> Romania is also the only participating country where not all permanent residents are covered by a health insurance. Due to these reasons the Romanian [[Romani people in Romania|Roma people]] typically neither have European insurance cards nor is their costs paid by the country of residence.{{cn|date=July 2017}}

It replaced the following medical forms:
* E110 - For international road [[haulier]]s
* E111 - For tourists
* E119 - For [[unemployment|unemployed people]]/[[job hunting|job seekers]]
* E128 - For students and workers in another member state

==Third party application processors==
European Health Insurance cards are provided free to all legal residents of participating countries. There are however various businesses who act as non-official agents on behalf of individuals, arranging supply of the cards in return for payment, often offering additional services such as the checking of applications for errors and general advice or assistance.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://redbpo.com/third-party-application-processors/ |title=Third Party Application Processors |publisher= |date=2016-09-02 |accessdate=2016-06-03}}</ref> This has proved extremely controversial. In 2010 the British government moved against companies that invited people to pay for the free EHIC, falsely implying that through payment the applicant could speed up the process.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-10925685 |title=BBC News - European health card scam stopped by OFT |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2010-08-10 |accessdate=2012-10-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consumerfocus.org.uk/wales/news/consumers-warned-to-be-search-engine-savvy |title=Consumers warned to be search engine savvy – Consumer Focus Wales |publisher=Consumerfocus.org.uk |date=2011-06-22 |accessdate=2012-10-12}}</ref> Despite this, the practice continues.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ray Massey |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2010441/Millions-duped-paying-free-EU-health-cards.html |title=Millions duped into paying for free EU health cards &#124; Mail Online |publisher=Dailymail.co.uk |date=2011-07-01 |accessdate=2012-10-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=James Coney |url=http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/holidays/article-2162077/EHIC-scam-warning--dont-pay-card.html |title=EHIC scam warning - don't pay for a card |publisher=This is Money |date=2012-06-20 |accessdate=2012-10-12}}</ref>

==Participating member states==
[[File:EU and EFTA.svg|thumb|The 32 participating member states, 28 EU (blue) and 4 EFTA (green).]]
As of 2013, 32 countries in Europe participate: the 31 [[member states of the European Economic Area]] (EEA) plus [[Switzerland]]. This includes the 28 [[member states of the European Union]] (EU) and 4 [[member states of the European Free Trade Association]] (EFTA).
