[[File:IMPAACT logo.jpg|thumb|right|IMPAACT logo]] The '''International Maternal Pediatric Adolescent AIDS Clinical Trials Group''', known as '''IMPAACT''', is a [[United States]]-based research network which studies [[HIV]] and [[AIDS]] in infant, pediatric, adolescent and pregnant women populations. It is a member of the [[Office of HIV/AIDS Network Coordination]] research group.
==Research== In 2012 IMPAACT published a study which found no link between the use of HIV medication and psychiatric illness in adolescents.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Nachman | first1 = S. | last2 = Chernoff | first2 = M. | last3 = Williams | first3 = P. | last4 = Hodge | first4 = J. | last5 = Heston | first5 = J. | last6 = Gadow | first6 = K. D. | title = Human Immunodeficiency Virus Disease Severity, Psychiatric Symptoms, and Functional Outcomes in Perinatally Infected Youth | doi = 10.1001/archpediatrics.2011.1785 | journal = Archives of Pediatrics and Adolescent Medicine | volume = 166 | issue = 6 | year = 2012 | pmid = | pmc = 3407294}}</ref>
==About== As of 2010, IMPAACT consisted of 39 domestic and 34 international clinical research sites.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nichd.nih.gov/research/supported/impaact.cfm |title=International Maternal-Pediatric-Adolescent AIDS Clinical Trials (IMPAACT) Group |first= |last= |work=nichd.nih.gov |year=2012 |accessdate=3 March 2012}}</ref>
