'''Rooming-in''' is the practice followed in hospitals and nursing homes where the baby's [[Baby crib|crib]] is kept by the side of the mother's bed.<ref name=tfd>{{cite web|last=The Free Dictionary|title=Meaning of Rooming-in|url=http://medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com/rooming-in|publisher=Farlex|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref> This arrangement gives an opportunity for the parents to know their baby.<ref>{{cite web|last=Medical news-nett|title="Rooming-in" benefits both mother and baby: New review|url=http://www.healtheast.org/maternity/rooming-in.html|accessdate=26 August 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130719033332/http://www.healtheast.org/maternity/rooming-in.html|archivedate=19 July 2013|df=}}</ref> The [[Parent-child bonding|bond]] between the parent and the child is well established in roomed-in babies. There is a better chance of success with [[Breastfeeding|breast-feeding]] in roomed-in babies.<ref>{{cite book|last=Park|first=K|title=Rooming-in|year=2011|publisher=Bhanot Brothers|location=Jalandhar|page=488}}</ref> Parents do not have the fear of baby-switching while roomed-in. Rooming-in is one of the components of [[Baby Friendly Hospital Initiative|baby-friendly hospital]]s, devised by [[WHO]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/272943/9789241513807-eng.pdf?ua=1|title=Baby-Friendly Hospital Initiative: Implementation Guidance|last=|first=|date=2018|website=World Health Organization|page=20|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
